Asia
----
[1] Bangladesh (Cox's Bazaar)
Date: Fri 10 Nov 2017, 11:47 PM
Source: Prothom-alo [edited]
http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/166035/Children-are-at-risk-from-outbreaks-of-measles


The government and UN partners have stepped up immunisation efforts in overcrowded camps and makeshift shelters of Rohingyas close to the border with Myanmar amid an increased number of suspected measles cases among the newly arrived Rohingyas and their host communities, reports UNB.

"Children are especially at risk from outbreaks of measles and other communicable diseases that result from the crowded living conditions, malnutrition and severe lack of water and sanitation in the camps and other sites," said Unicef Bangladesh representative Edouard Beigbeder.

"To halt any wider outbreak, it's essential that coordinated efforts begin immediately to protect as many children as possible," the official was quoted as saying in a message received from UNICEF on [Fri 10 Nov 2017] night.

Nearly 360 000 people in the age group of 6 months -- 15 years among the new Rohingya arrivals in Cox's Bazar and their host communities, irrespective of their immunisation status, will be administered measles and rubella vaccines through fixed health facilities, outreach vaccination teams, and at entry points into Bangladesh.

Measles, a childhood killer disease which can be particularly dangerous among unimmunised and malnourished children, is one of the major health risks among the over 613 000 people who have crossed over to Bangladesh from Myanmar since late August [2017] and are now living in cramped and insanitary conditions in Cox's Bazar district.

As of [Sat 4 Nov 2017], 1 death and 412 suspected cases of measles have been reported among the vulnerable populations living in camps, settlements, and among the host communities in Cox's Bazar. Of them, 352 cases are from Ukhia and 46 from Teknaf upazilas, and 11 have been reported from the district hospital. The majority of cases - 398 - are among the new arrivals and 14 among the host communities. As many as 82 percent cases are among children under 5 years of age.

With the risk of measles being high during such health emergencies, the health and family welfare ministry with support of WHO, UNICEF and other local partners, was quick to roll out a measles and rubella (MR) vaccination campaign, between [16 Sep and 4 Oct 2017], within weeks of the start of the recent influx of Rohingyas from Myanmar. Nearly 136 000 children between 6 months and 15 years were administered MR vaccine. Additionally, around 72 000 children up to 5 years of age were given bivalent oral polio vaccine (bOPV) and a dose of Vitamin A to help prevent measles related complication.

The number of new arrivals has increased since the MR campaign, which also had challenges reaching out to all children in view of movement of people within the camps and settlements.

WHO representative to Bangladesh N Paranietharan said as part of stepped up vaccination efforts, 43 fixed health facility sites, 56 outreach vaccination teams and vaccination teams at main border entry points will administer MR vaccine to population aged 6 months -- 15 years, along with oral polio vaccine to children under 5 years and TT vaccine to pregnant women.

"These efforts are aimed at protecting and preventing the spread of measles among the vulnerable population," said the WHO official.

Over 70 vaccinators from government and partners have been trained to deliver routine vaccination through fixed sites and outreach teams beginning on [Sat 11 Nov 2017], while vaccination at entry points at Subrang, Teknaf, is ongoing since [1 Nov 2017].

To improve hygiene conditions among the refugee population, 3.2 million water purification tablets and a total of 18 418 hygiene kits have been distributed benefitting 92 090 people.

The current initiative is yet another massive vaccination drive being rolled out for the new arrivals from Myanmar and their host communities in Cox's Bazar since [25 Aug 2017].

After covering 136 000 people in the September-October [2017] MR campaign, the ministry and partners administered 900 000 doses of oral cholera vaccine to these vulnerable populations in 2 phases.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since violence erupted across Rakhine State, Myanmar, on 25 Aug 2017, more than half a million people have poured across the border between Myanmar and Bangladesh. They have joined the more than 200 000 others who had came in previous cross-border influxes.

Almost 60 percent of the refugees are children, all of whom have suffered tremendous loss. As violence continues in Myanmar, their numbers and their needs grow. UNICEF is on the ground working with the Bangladeshi authorities and partners to help meet the Rohingya refugees' urgent needs (excerpted and edited UNICEF).

Since measles is a vaccine-preventable disease, it is one positive action UNICEF can take to reduce risk in these crowded living and unsanitary conditions.

A Healthmap of Bangladesh can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5441554,153. - Mod.LK]

